Adam Lanza, and Eric Harris, and Dylan Klebold, and Nikolas Cruz and others - came back to the school where they were rejected. Healing from such horrific events starts when we, as communities, realize that we share some responsibility of their murderous actions.

We raise angry boys and we don't feel responsible for them. As long as we keep doing that, we will have mass shooters. If we want to transform this culture of cruelty and humiliation, we ought to take responsibility.
Their community failed them. Rejected them. In many cases, their community dehumanized them. They were socially isolated. Miserably.
The gunmen come back to the school where they felt rejected. Where they were oftentimes ignored or bullied.
I am not familiar with today's mass shooting. However, in general, I can say with some authority that in many mass shootings in schools, there's a pattern.
We all know those young guys in our schools. Today's shooter from Florida was known to the school administrators, teachers and students.
Now think about that young dude. About the hours he spends online, looking for attention. Googling "how to be a real man." First page results:https://www.puatraining.com/blog/how-to-be-man
In other cases, they were just, ya know, different. Not the athletic type, not too smart, no friends. No one say with them in the cafeteria during lunch. Because, ya know, weirdo.

If you do, you will see that many of the gunmen we're student of the school they came back to. Many of them were what Americans like to call "troubled," which is oftentimes a codeword for a weirdo; in some cases they were bullied.
Read the report that came out after the Columbine shooting (conducted by the departure of education and the secret service. 50 pages long. Good reading). Read about other school shootings.
Do your goddamn research. The FBI and CDC websites are a good start. Lots of numbers out there. See for yourself. Mass shootings aren't tragedy. They are outcome.

Read about trauma. About intergenerational trauma. About homelessness. About poverty. About the opioid epidemic. About suicide rates and overdose rates. All of those are interconnected. Mass shootings don't occur in a vacuum.
Read about WASP culture and ideology. The norms. The individualism. The meritocracy. The foundations of this current painful culture.
But it takes lots of courage and vulnerable. It takes willingness to admit your history. Genocide of native American. Enslavement of Africans. Go the fuck back. All the way back.
If you want to change mass shooting, you out to transform the DNA of your culture. It's possible. Cultures aren't a fixed reality. They change all the freakin' time.
It's also rooted in individualism and competition, in this systemic "winners and losers" way of thinking, being, behaving.

Mass shooting isn't a tragedy. It's  embedded in this country's DNA, its history. As a social phenomenal, it's rooted in hyper-capitalism, hyper-consumarism neoliberalism, exploitation, dehumanization.
